<section class="slop-section" aria-labelledby="slop-heading">
    <div class="slop-header">
        <div class="slop-label">Reference</div>
        <h2 id="slop-heading">What is <em>&ldquo;slop&rdquo;</em>?</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="slop-content">
        <div class="slop-main">
            <p>
                <strong>Slop</strong> is internet shorthand for low-effort, AI-generated content
                published at scale &mdash; articles, comments, reviews, and social posts churned out
                by language models with little or no human editing.
            </p>
            <p>
                The term emerged in 2024 as LLM-generated text began flooding search results,
                product reviews, LinkedIn feeds, and news sites. Unlike thoughtful AI-assisted
                writing, slop is characterised by its formulaic structure, hollow confidence,
                and lack of genuine insight.
            </p>
            <p>
                SlopTotal doesn&rsquo;t judge <em>all</em> AI use. Humans editing AI drafts,
                using AI for brainstorming, or collaborating with AI tools is not slop.
                What we detect is the telltale fingerprint of text that was generated wholesale
                and published without meaningful human involvement.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="slop-signals">
            <h3>Common slop signals</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <span class="signal-icon signal-icon--phrase"></span>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Formulaic phrases</strong>
                        <span>&ldquo;In today&rsquo;s rapidly evolving landscape&rdquo;, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s important to note&rdquo;, &ldquo;delve into&rdquo;</span>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="signal-icon signal-icon--structure"></span>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Rigid structure</strong>
                        <span>Numbered lists, &ldquo;Firstly / Secondly / Moreover&rdquo; stacking, five-paragraph essay format</span>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="signal-icon signal-icon--tone"></span>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Hedging &amp; filler</strong>
                        <span>Excessive qualifiers, hollow conclusions, saying a lot while conveying little</span>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="signal-icon signal-icon--stats"></span>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Statistical fingerprints</strong>
                        <span>Low perplexity, uniform burstiness, predictable token distributions</span>
                    </div>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
